docs.abstract: The stakes are high for Bethesda’s newest role-playing game. Microsoft needs an Xbox hit, and players are hungry for an expansive and satisfying space adventure.
docs.snippet: The stakes are high for Bethesda’s newest role-playing game. Microsoft needs an Xbox hit, and players are hungry for an expansive and satisfying space adventure.
docs.lead_paragraph: Starfield almost immediately nudges its players to the edges of the cosmos. In the opening hours of the role-playing video game, it’s possible to land your spaceship on Earth’s moon or zip 16 light-years from a remote outpost to Alpha Centauri. When you open your map and zoom out from a planet, you can behold its surrounding solar system; zoom out again, and you’re scrolling past luminous stars and the mysterious worlds that orbit them.

headline.main: Starfield’s 1,000 Planets May Be One Giant Leap for Game Design

byline.original: By Kellen Browning and Matt Stevens

docs.abstract: The leaders of Google, OpenAI, Microsoft and others are meeting with lawmakers on Sept. 13 to kick off listening sessions that may shape A.I. rules in the United States.
docs.snippet: The leaders of Google, OpenAI, Microsoft and others are meeting with lawmakers on Sept. 13 to kick off listening sessions that may shape A.I. rules in the United States.
docs.lead_paragraph: Senator Chuck Schumer, Democrat of New York, plans to kick off a series of listening sessions next month on the regulation of artificial intelligence with Elon Musk of Tesla, Sundar Pichai of Google, Sam Altman of OpenAI and Satya Nadella of Microsoft.

headline.main: Tech Chiefs to Gather in Washington Next Month on A.I. Regulations
headline.print_headline: Tech Chiefs to Meet in Washington on Regulating A.I.

docs.abstract: As the tech giants found their financial footing last quarter, they doubled down on artificial intelligence, which has been a boon to companies like Nvidia.
docs.snippet: As the tech giants found their financial footing last quarter, they doubled down on artificial intelligence, which has been a boon to companies like Nvidia.
docs.lead_paragraph: A year ago, the tech industry’s prospects looked bleak. Google’s profit dropped. Shares of Facebook’s parent company, Meta, were in free fall. Business growth at Amazon had slowed to its lowest level in two decades.

headline.main: Big Tech Rebounds and Preps for Transformative A.I. Investments
headline.print_headline: Big Tech Rallies and Channels Its New Momentum Into A.I.

docs.lead_paragraph: Marietje Schaake’s résumé is full of notable roles: Dutch politician who served for a decade in the European Parliament, international policy director at Stanford University’s Cyber Policy Center, adviser to several nonprofits and governments.

headline.main: What Can You Do When A.I. Lies About You?
headline.print_headline: If A.I. Tells a Lie About You, What Can You Do? Not Much.

docs.abstract: Apple, Nvidia, Tesla and Microsoft are among the giants that have tumbled by at least 10 percent in the past month after powering a market rally earlier this year.
docs.snippet: Apple, Nvidia, Tesla and Microsoft are among the giants that have tumbled by at least 10 percent in the past month after powering a market rally earlier this year.
docs.lead_paragraph: In the span of a month, the bottom has dropped out of the bull-market rally as investors have come to grips with the prospect of “higher for longer” interest rates worldwide. The sell-off in global stocks and bonds picked up steam on Thursday. And weary market watchers will be looking for more hints on the Fed’s view at next week’s Jackson Hole summit of central bankers and policymakers.

headline.main: Interest Rate Jitters Sink the Heavyweights of Tech

byline.original: By Andrew Ross Sorkin, Ravi Mattu, Bernhard Warner, Sarah Kessler, Lauren Hirsch and Ephrat Livni

docs.abstract: An acquisition that once faced long odds now appears to be on a path toward approval.
docs.snippet: An acquisition that once faced long odds now appears to be on a path toward approval.
docs.lead_paragraph: British antitrust officials said on Tuesday that they were reviewing a revised offer by Microsoft to win approval of its $69 billion merger with Activision Blizzard, an effort to clear the biggest remaining regulatory hurdle to the major video games deal.

headline.main: Microsoft Offers British Regulators Changes to Activision Deal
headline.print_headline: Microsoft Offers Changes  To Salvage Activision Deal
